{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512504","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512504"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:56:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:56:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11909"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11909","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11909"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.49,0.03,0.08,0.12,0.28]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4505"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78107"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4505","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4505"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11909"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63529"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1254"},{"type":"tags","id":"1694"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6639"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6653"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26796"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26804"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44368"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44951"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78107","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78107"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 19-year-old man presents to his General Practitioner with a one day history of sore throat, odynophagia, and malaise. He has a dry cough but does not feel short of breath. There is no fever or rash. This is his fourth similar presentation this year.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECardiorespiratory examination is unremarkable and vital signs are within normal ranges.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"According to the Centor criteria, the presence of which one of the following would make a viral cause of this presentation more likely than bacterial cause?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Presence of a dry cough","Wheeze","Erythematous tonsils with exudate","Cervical lymphadenopathy","Rhinorrhoea"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis question requires knowledge of the modified Centor criteria and its application to clinical practice. The Centor criteria is used to determine the likelihood of group A streptococcal (GAS) infection in adults. The modified Centor criteria includes:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Efever \u0026gt; 38C\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Etonsillar exudate\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eabsence of a cough\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ecervical lymphadenopathy\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA score of 3 or greater, increases the likelihood that the tonsillitis is bacterial (GAS) in origin, and will therefore require antibiotics. In this case the clinical presentation is most in keeping with viral tonsillitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003E\u2018presence of a dry cough\u2019\u003C/strong\u003E. According to the modified Centor criteria, \u00a0absence of a cough increases the likelihood of a GAS \u003Cstrong\u003Ebacterial \u003C/strong\u003Etonsillitis. This patient has a dry cough, which is more suggestive of viral tonsillitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u2018Wheeze\u2019\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Wheeze is not part of the Centor criteria and would not differentiate viral from bacterial tonsillitis. An inspiratory wheeze or stridor indicates an upper airway obstruction and may indicate the severity of tonsillitis in terms of causing a partial airway obstruction. An expiratory wheeze is typically heard due to pathology of the lower/smaller airways.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u00a0\u003Cstrong\u003E\u2018Erythematous tonsils with exudate\u2019\u003C/strong\u003E are associated with a bacterial aetiology, as well as \u003Cstrong\u003E\u2018cervical lymphadenopathy\u2019\u003C/strong\u003E, according to the modified Centor criteria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst \u003Cstrong\u003Erhinorrhoea\u003C/strong\u003E may be more suggestive of a viral aetiology, this is not part of the Centor criteria in differentiating viral from bacterial tonsillitis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Tonsilitis can be of viral or bacterial origin.","Physical examination can assist in differentiating between bacterial and viral tonsillitis.","The modified Centor criteria can be used to determine the likelihood that tonsillitis is of a bacterial origin (group A B-haemolytic streptococcus) (GAS)."],"references":["Aalbers, J., O\u0027Brien, K.K., Chan, WS. Falk AG, Teljeur C, Dimitrov BD, Fahey T. Predicting streptococcal pharyngitis in adults in primary care: a systematic review of the diagnostic accuracy of symptoms and signs and validation of the Centor score. BMC Med [Internet]. 2011 [cited 24 Jan 2022]; 9(67). Available from: https://bmcmedicine.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/1741-7015-9-67#citeas  DOI: https://doi.org/10.1186/1741-7015-9-67","Murgia V, Manti S, Licari A, De Filippo M, Ciprandi G, Marseglia GL. Upper Respiratory Tract Infection-Associated Acute Cough and the Urge to Cough: New Insights for Clinical Practice. Pediatr Allergy Immunol Pulmonol. 2020 Mar;33(1):3-11. doi: 10.1089/ped.2019.1135. PMID: 33406022; PMCID: PMC7875114. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7875114/","Footitt J, Johnston SL. Cough and viruses in airways disease: mechanisms. Pulm Pharmacol Ther. 2009 Apr;22(2):108-13. doi: 10.1016/j.pupt.2008.12.022. PMID: 19480062; PMCID: PMC7110775. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7110775/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63529"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11909"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63529","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63529"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-09T13:47:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-09T13:49:49+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4505"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78107"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:40:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"da